  "updatedAt": "2026-05-14T09:00:00Z",
  "content": "\n# How to Choose a Bathroom Contractor in Chandler: 15 Questions to Ask\n\nHiring a contractor to remodel your bathroom is a major decision. The quality of their work will impact your daily life, your home's structure, and your property value. In the East Valley, where master-planned developments, strict HOA rules, and hard water challenges are common, finding the right **bathroom contractor in Chandler, AZ** requires thorough vetting. \n\nBefore you sign any remodeling agreement, protect your investment by asking these 15 essential questions.\n\n---\n\n## Vetting Licensing, Insurance, & Credentials\n\n### 1. Do you hold an active license with the Arizona Registrar of Contractors (ROC)?\nIn Arizona, anyone performing remodeling work must be licensed by the ROC. Unlicensed handymen cannot legally pull permits and do not offer recourse if they abandon the job or perform substandard work.\n*   *Why it matters:* ARZ Home Remodeling is licensed under **ROC #ROC338304**. You can verify any contractor's license on the [Arizona ROC portal](https://roc.az.gov).\n\n### 2. What classification is your license, and what are its limits?\nContractors have specific classifications (e.g., residential, commercial, dual). Make sure their license covers the scope of your residential bathroom project.\n\n### 3. Do you carry active general liability and workers' compensation insurance?\nIf a worker is injured on your property or a pipe bursts and floods your hallway, the contractor's insurance must cover the damages. Always ask for a copy of their insurance certificate.\n\n---\n\n## Vetting Technical Expertise & Local Regulations\n\n### 4. What shower waterproofing system do you install?\nTraditional cement boards and plastic sheeting are prone to failure. Ask if they use advanced, bonded sheet membranes.\n*   *Local standard:* We use the [Schluter-KERDI waterproofing system](/blog/schluter-kerdi-vs-redgard-arizona/) on all custom shower builds to ensure a completely vapor-tight, leak-proof substrate.\n\n### 5. Will you pull the required permits from the City of Chandler?\nAny structural changes, plumbing relocations, or electrical upgrades require a permit from the **City of Chandler Development Services Dept**. A contractor who asks you to pull the permit as an \"owner-builder\" is trying to avoid liability.\n*   *Our process:* We handle all city permit filings and structural inspections. Learn more about the permitting rules in our guide to [bathroom remodeling permits in Chandler](/bathroom-remodeling-permits-chandler/).\n\n### 6. How do you handle HOA compliance in Chandler master-planned communities?\nNeighborhoods like Ocotillo, Fulton Ranch, and Sun Lakes have strict guidelines regarding dumpster placement, work hours, and noise. Your contractor must know how to coordinate with your HOA board.\n\n---\n\n## Vetting Project Execution & Schedule\n\n### 7. Who will manage the job site on a daily basis?\nEnsure there is a dedicated, English-speaking project manager on-site to answer your questions, coordinate sub-trades, and verify the quality of work daily.\n\n### 8. What is your estimated project timeline, and is it guaranteed?\nA standard guest bath should take 2 to 3 weeks; a master bath should take 4 to 6 weeks. Ask for a day-by-day project schedule before demo begins. You can review a typical timeline in our [bathroom remodeling timeline](/bathroom-remodeling-timeline/) guide.\n\n### 9. Will my project be worked on consecutively, or will workers disappear for days?\nSome contractors start demolition, disappear to work on other jobs, and leave you without a functioning bathroom. Ask for a commitment that your job will be worked on every business day until completion.\n\n### 10. How will you protect the rest of my home from dust and debris?\nTearing out drywall and tile creates massive amounts of dust. The contractor must seal off the workspace with heavy plastic sheeting, protect your wood or carpeted hallways, and use dust-extraction vacuums.\n\n---\n\n## Vetting Financials & Pricing\n\n### 11. Is your written proposal a fixed-price contract or an estimate?\nAvoid \"time and materials\" agreements. Demand a detailed, itemized, fixed-price contract that outlines the exact materials, labor, and permit fees. Any changes should require a written change order signed by you.\n\n### 12. What is your payment schedule?\nNever pay more than 10% to 15% upfront. Payments should be tied to clear construction milestones (e.g., demolition complete, rough-in plumbing approved, tiling complete, final walkthrough).\n\n### 13. Do you offer financing options for qualified homeowners?\nRemodeling is a significant investment. Ask if they partner with local lenders to offer competitive financing or payment plans. We offer options to help keep your project budget manageable; view our [bathroom remodeling financing](/bathroom-remodeling-financing/) options.\n\n---\n\n## Vetting Quality Assurance & Reputation\n\n### 14. What warranty do you provide on your workmanship?\nArizona law requires a minimum warranty period, but top contractors offer longer protection. \n*   *Our standard:* We provide a **2-year written workmanship warranty** on every bathroom remodel, standing behind every tile joint and plumbing connection.\n\n### 15. Can you provide three references from recent Chandler bathroom projects?\nSpeak with recent clients who had similar work completed. Ask them about the contractor's cleanliness, communication, and if they completed the project on budget.\n\nChoosing the right partner is the difference between a stressful renovation and a smooth, successful transformation. At ARZ Home Remodeling, we are proud of our local reputation, licensing (**ROC #ROC338304**), and commitment to quality. Contact Mike Hernandez and our team at **(520) 569-3339** to ask your questions and schedule your free, itemized estimate.\n  "
